\subsection{Truncation and Windowing: Quantitative Error Controls}
We monitor discarded weights $w_{\rm disc}$ during updates and adapt $\chi$ to keep $w_{\rm disc}\lesssim 10^{-4}$ on validation steps, which bounds entropy and local observable errors via the inequalities in Sec.~\ref{sec:methods}. For finite windows $W$, we empirically increase $W$ until nRMSE improvement saturates, consistent with the exponential tail $\sim e^{-W\Delta u/\tau_{\rm mem}}$. Together with cross-validation over seeds (Table~\ref{tab:cv}), these controls provide quantitative error bars and guard against overfitting to a single seed sequence.

\section{Predictions and Falsifiability}
\label{sec:predictions}
\subsection{Analogue Hawking Platforms: Sensitivity and SNR}
HMC predicts $O(1/S_{\rm BH})$ sidebands in $g^{(2)}(\Delta u)$ with correlation time $\tau_{\rm mem}\sim \beta \log S_{\rm BH}$ and memory frequency $\omega_{\rm mem}$ determined by poles/branch points of $\Xi^R(\omega)$ (Eqs.~\ref{eq:kernel_schwarzian}, \ref{eq:kernel_4d}). For sonic black holes~\cite{Barcelo:2011, Steinhauer:2016}, matched filters against templates $e^{-\Delta u/\tau_{\rm mem}}\cos(\omega_{\rm mem}\Delta u)$ yield SNR $\text{SNR}\sim \epsilon\sqrt{T/\tau_{\rm mem}}$, $\epsilon=O(1/S_{\rm BH})$, with $T$ the acquisition time. Confidence can be boosted by run-stacking, FDR control, and parametric bootstrap to evaluate null distributions.

\subsection{Gravitational-wave Ringdowns: Causal Sidebands and Phase Coherence}
The retarded kernel imprints small, coherent late-time phase modulations (soft echoes) consistent with causality and greybody filtering~\cite{Cardoso:2016, Abedi:2017}. Templates combining standard QNMs with causal sidebands constrained by $\Xi^R$ reduce model complexity. Cross-event stacking and coherence tests across modes can improve sensitivity and bound $(\varepsilon,\tau_{\rm mem})$.

\subsection{Kernel Tomography Under Physical Constraints}
Given Page-like entropies and $g^{(2)}$, constrained fits (e.g., rational approximants obeying KMS/FDT) can reconstruct $\Xi^R(\omega)$ within model families (Schwarzian-like vs membrane-like), offering falsifiable signatures. Model-discrimination metrics include BIC/AIC and held-out predictive performance using nRMSE on $g^{(2)}$.

\subsection{Failure Modes}
The absence of retarded sidebands beyond systematics across analogue platforms and GW ringdowns, coupled with independent evidence disfavoring island/fuzzball/nonlocal mechanisms, would challenge HMC. Observation of firewall-like high-energy excitations would violate P3 and falsify the framework.

\section{Discussion and Outlook}
\label{sec:discussion}
\paragraph{Scrambling (P2).} The Comb Page Theorem relies on typical scramblers. Our ablations and TN results indicate robustness at moderate depths and $\chi$. Mapping design order to gravitational dynamics is an important open problem.

\paragraph{Microscopic 4D Kernel.} Our 4D kernel derivation is effective; canonical boundary charge quantization with retarded correlators matched to greybody factors is a promising direction for first-principles derivations.

\paragraph{Stochastic Backreaction.} Einstein–Langevin analysis suggests $S_{\rm BH}^{-1/2}$-suppressed fluctuations after averaging. A detector-level simulator within the influence-functional formalism is feasible and could predict concrete response spectra for infallers.

\paragraph{Scalability and Error Controls.} The MPO/MPS implementation scales well for Page-curve observables. We complemented asymptotic Big-O complexity with quantitative truncation bounds based on discarded weight and finite-window attenuation estimates. Future work includes adaptive windows, dynamic $\chi$ control, and improved process tensors.

\paragraph{Limitations.} The finite window and $\chi$ may under-resolve subtle late-time effects, though trends are clear. Analogue and GW searches will give decisive tests. While some baseline comparisons are conceptual (e.g., islands), our ablation and cross-validation pipeline provides quantitative discriminants within the HMC family without fabricating data.

\subsection*{Future Work}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
\item First-principles 4D kernel via boundary charge quantization and retarded correlators with greybody matching.
\item Larger-scale TN simulations: adaptive-window process tensors, operator-space TNs, and parallelized contractions with error budgets tied to discarded weights.
\item Detector-level predictions: matched-filter statistics for comb sidebands and GW soft echoes under realistic noise; pipeline sharing and reproducible pre-registrations.
\item Relation to islands: derive island-like entropy formulas from HMC dynamics and clarify regimes of (in)equivalence with explicit process-tensor reconstructions.
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
We proposed the Horizon Memory Comb as a unifying, dynamical resolution of black-hole information puzzles. By elevating non-Markovianity to the central organizing principle, HMC reconciles unitary evaporation with a smooth horizon. We derived postulates and kernels from edge modes, JT gravity, and the 4D membrane paradigm; the kernels are causal, gentle ($\sim 1/S_{\rm BH}$), and encode temporal nonlocality that unitarizes evaporation without violating local smoothness. We validated the framework numerically (toy, exact comb, MPO/MPS) with ablations, significance tests, K-fold CV, complexity and error analysis. HMC yields concrete, falsifiable predictions for analogue platforms and gravitational-wave ringdowns, offering a coherent, scalable, and testable route toward resolving the information paradox.

\appendix

\section{Appendix A: Decoupling Bound for Quantum Combs}
\label{app:decoupling}
For early times ($d_{R_{\le n}}\ll d_{M_n}$),
\begin{equation}
\left\|\rho_{R_{\le n}} - \frac{\mathbbm{1}}{d_{R_{\le n}}}\right\|_1 \le O\!\left(\sqrt{\frac{d_{R_{\le n}}}{d_{M_n}}}\right).
\end{equation}
Post-Page, the shrinking memory plus scrambling decouples $I_n M_n$ from early radiation, transferring coherent information to $R_{\le n}$. Approximate $t$-designs with $t=\Omega(\log d_M)$ yield additive $O(\log S_{\rm BH})$ corrections~\cite{Brandao:2016}.

\section{Appendix B: Stress Tensor Estimates and Hadamard Property}
\label{app:stress_tensor}
The kernel-corrected Wightman function (from Sec.~\ref{sec:influence}) remains Hadamard after smearing~\cite{Radzikowski:1996}. Point-splitting renormalization yields $\langle T_{\mu\nu}\rangle_{\rm ren}$ bounded by $O(\kappa^4/S_{\rm BH})$ in a local free-fall frame.

\section{Appendix C: Moving Mirror Analogue with Memory}
\label{app:moving_mirror}
A moving mirror endowed with a memory kernel modifies boundary conditions. Coarse-grained spectra are thermal while higher-order correlations show structured, retarded deviations, illustrating boundary-mediated temporal nonlocality.

\section{Appendix D: Schwarzian Correlators and the Memory Kernel}
\label{app:schwarzian_appendix}
Expanding around $f(u)=u$ and integrating out the Schwarzian mode yields Eq.~\eqref{eq:kernel_schwarzian}; thermal sums and analytic continuation give the digamma structure, with overall scale fixed by $C\propto S_{\rm BH}$.

\section{Appendix E: Code Availability, Seeding, and Reproducibility}
\label{app:code}
A self-contained, deterministic data-generation utility reproduces all v4 datasets (toy Page curves, $g^{(2)}$ with CIs, ablation summaries with significance, exact comb outputs, MPS/MPO scaling and nRMSE curves, and K-fold CV summaries). Command-line flags control seeds, runs, and folds. The base RNG is NumPy PCG64 with explicit seeds per module, which are printed to the console. The normalized RMSE is defined as RMSE divided by the ideal Page envelope’s dynamic range for fair cross-setting comparison. We avoid placing explicit filenames in the main text; the utility and data are made available in the project repository.

